Machine Learning Mutual Fund Three Year Returns¶

Note this notebook only shows 3 year returns¶
Summary¶

From analyzing various metrics, three year returns were predominantly influenced by weightings in different sectors such as stock portfolio weightings, financial services weighting, consumer cyclical weighting, technology, and healthcare weighting. SVM showed fairly high accuracy, precision, and recall with these five variables ~85%, with even higher metrics score when modeling consumer cyclical and technology weightings. It is shown that higher weighting in technology, lower weighting in financial services, and a narrow range from consumer cyclical weighting showed to influence the model of classifying a fund as 1 (beats market returns + fees) or 0 (does not beat market returns). Other machine learning techniques such as SGDClassifier, Randomforest, and KNN classifier where also analyzed, where the Randomforest showed to have the highest metrics (>90%). The Randomforest ensemble was highly impacted by consumer cyclical, technology, and stock portfolio weightings in similar ways.

Background¶

In this analysis we dive into a mutual funds data set scraped from Yahoo Finance in 2018. We analyze how different weightings of sectors could influence mutual fund returns for 3 year and 5 year annualized average returns. The data set contains 125 columns/variables, however many of these variables will be excluded from our analysis because they are either irrelevant (i.e inception date, fund name, fund family), or they are a function of fund returns and would thus be redundant correlations (i.e risk ratios like beta, alpha, sharpe). Some variables that would be of interest are predominantly weightings in sectors such stock, bonds, healthcare, technology, and etc. We will further reduce our variables to variables that have higher correlations with fund returns and then apply SVM (Support Vector Machines) to our features to predict if either (1) the fund has superior returns, meaning they return enough to beat the S&P500 including expenses (in this analysis we are only given information on expense ratios and no other fees such as "load" fees), and (0) the fund is non-superior, and do not beat the S&P 500.

Caution¶

Large assumptions are made for the sake of this project and may not reflect highly accurate on reality. (1) We assume that the portfolio weightings reported in 2018 do not change drastically over the 3 and 5 year time frame. For example if a mutual fund deploys a strategy of 60% tech, 20% healthcare, 10% utilities, 5% bonds, and 5% others, we will assume that mutual fund has held onto the strategy of higher weighting in tech and healthcare and did not drastically change in the last 3-5 years. (2) In reality many of these funds will have "load" fees, this can range from anywhere to 3-8%, for the case of this analysis we will assume a low end of 3% load fee is included for all mutual funds.

Labels¶

The labels that will be used are the "fund_return_3years" and "fund_return_5years." These are trailing average returns including dividends earned, for example 3 years will include returns from 2018, 2017, and 2016. We use these labels because it will evaluate the performance of the strategy employed in the last 3-5 years. ** CAUTION This conclusion would only be of use if an investor agrees with (1) the assumptions made priorly stated, and (2) that the strategy employed by the mutual funds will continue to be successful into the future

Converting Three Year Return to Binary¶

1 = superior return

0 = non-superior

Need to make sure we have even distribution of both superior and non-superior

In [119]:
df3.fund_return_3years.hist(figsize=(10,5), color='g', bins=30)
plt.title('3 Year Fund Return')
plt.xlabel('Percent Return')
plt.ylabel('count')

print("3 years fund return is", df3.fund_return_3years.mean())

3 years fund return is 6.996638878964687

It looks like the middle is around 7%. The S&P 500 average return in 5 years from 2014-2018 is 6.68% and 3 years 2016-2018 is 7.57%, somewhat similar to the average return on mutual funds. However, mutual funds will have an expense ratio on average of 1.12% (at least in this dataset) and if it is a loaded fund it could have a fee anywhere from 3-8% added. So in order for an investor to be more profitable than the market (after fees) they would need a fund that returns >13.12% (7% avg + %1.12 + 3%(assume low load fee). Thus, a superior mutual fund classified as 1 would have to return >13.12%, for simplicity we will use 13%.

However we still need to make the number classifications (1's = superior and 0's = non-superior) as evenly as possible, so we will have to pick at random <13% and number of data points equal to the number of data points above 13%

Fund Returns Data: since very high returns are a needle in a haystack and are usually for 1% net worth investors, we will get rid of anything over 30% return. We will also get rid of returns <20%, or, very poor performance since this is unusual for a mutual fund to stay in business and perform so badly.

It would also make sense that an investor may want to invest in a mutual fund that is at least somewhat diversified, even if it is just a little. Thus we will drop funds that are over 90% weighting in an individual sector

#code privded by https://jakevdp.github.io/PythonDataScienceHandbook/05.07-support-vector-machines.html
def plot_svc_decision_function(model, ax=None, plot_support=True):
    """Plot the decision function for a 2D SVC"""
    if ax is None:
        ax = plt.gca()
    xlim = ax.get_xlim()
    ylim = ax.get_ylim()
    
    # create grid to evaluate model
    x = np.linspace(xlim[0], xlim[1], 30)
    y = np.linspace(ylim[0], ylim[1], 30)
    Y, X = np.meshgrid(y, x)
    xy = np.vstack([X.ravel(), Y.ravel()]).T
    P = model.decision_function(xy).reshape(X.shape)
    
    # plot decision boundary and margins
    ax.contour(X, Y, P, colors='k',
               levels=[-1, 0, 1], alpha=0.5,
               linestyles=['--', '-', '--'])
    
    # plot support vectors
    if plot_support:
        ax.scatter(model.support_vectors_[:, 0],
                   model.support_vectors_[:, 1],
                   s=300, linewidth=1, facecolors='none');
    ax.set_xlim(xlim)
    ax.set_ylim(ylim)

Note¶

In [315]:
#code privded by https://jakevdp.github.io/PythonDataScienceHandbook/05.07-support-vector-machines.html
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 6))
fig.subplots_adjust(left=0.0625, right=0.95, wspace=0.1)

for axi, C in zip(ax, [5.0, 0.1]):
    model = SVC(kernel='linear', C=C).fit(x_train, y_train)
    axi.scatter(x_train[:, 0], x_train[:, 1], c=y_train, s=50, cmap='plasma')
    plot_svc_decision_function(model, axi)
    axi.scatter(model.support_vectors_[:, 0],
                model.support_vectors_[:, 1],
                s=300, lw=1, facecolors='none');
    axi.set_title('C = {0:.1f}'.format(C), size=14)

Improving the Model by Outliers¶

From looking at the SVM plots we can see there is a lot of misclassification where consumer_cycical (x-axis) is weighted 0 and some points were consumer_cyclical is greater than 0.4. If very low consumer_cyclical values are eliminated as well as very high values, we should hope to increase recall, precision, and accuracy. We will eliminate any scaled weightings that are below 0.05 in consumer cyclical

def plot_roc_curve(fpr, tpr, label=None):
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, linewidth=2, label=label)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    plt.axis([0, 1, 0, 1])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
